<methodology slug="competitor-analysis">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>research</group>
    <domain>researcher</domain>
    <summary>Systematic 5-step framework for studying direct, indirect, and future competitors across 8 dimensions to identify gaps and define defensible differentiation.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>competitor-analysis</tag>
      <tag>positioning</tag>
      <tag>market-research</tag>
      <tag>differentiation</tag>
      <tag>gap-analysis</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-28</created>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>Competitor Analysis</title>

    <summary>A 5-step framework for systematically studying businesses competing for the same customers: identify (direct / indirect / future), map on a positioning matrix, analyse across 8 dimensions, find gaps, then define differentiation. Output is competitive-analysis.md in .aidocs/product_docs/.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Entrepreneurs either ignore competitors ("we're unique") or copy them without strategy. Without a structured competitive scan you miss indirect competitors, build table-stakes features instead of differentiators, and produce pricing that fits no segment well. A gap-driven analysis converts a competitor landscape into a concrete positioning statement and feature roadmap.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Pre-MVP: 5-10 candidate competitors identified, need structured scan before committing engineering time.</item>
        <item>Positioning sprint: landing page or pricing rewrite requiring a defensible differentiation statement.</item>
        <item>New feature greenlight: comparing how 3-7 incumbents implement a feature you plan to build.</item>
        <item>Quarterly market refresh: re-scoring known competitors on price, features, and traction.</item>
        <item>Investor / pitch deck: building a credible competitor matrix slide with named gaps.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Deep customer-pain discovery—competitors are a proxy, not a substitute for user interviews; use pain-points or problem-validation first.</item>
        <item>Pure brainstorming with no category defined yet—run idea-generation-methods first.</item>
        <item>Regulated / B2B-enterprise procurement where pricing is hidden behind sales—agents will hallucinate numbers.</item>
        <item>Real-time monitoring of a single competitor—use a change-tracking service (Visualping), not a one-shot agent run.</item>
        <item>"Should we build this?" gut checks—competitor count alone does not answer that.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="competitor-types">
      <p>Identifying all three competitor types to avoid false sense of whitespace.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Identify all three competitor types: direct (same product, same audience), indirect (different product, same problem), and future (emerging or could pivot). Target 5-10 direct, 3-5 indirect, 2-3 future.</statement>
        <rationale>Analysing only direct competitors misses the substitutes customers actually use and the entrants who will arrive in 18 months.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <p>Sources for discovery: Google "[problem] solution", Product Hunt category search, G2/Capterra category browse, "Alternatives to [known competitor]", Reddit "What do you use for [problem]?", direct customer interviews.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="positioning-matrix">
      <p>Visual mapping of competitor positions to identify empty quadrants and underserved market segments.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Plot each competitor on a 2-axis matrix (price vs feature breadth) and identify empty quadrants or underserved positions before selecting your own positioning.</statement>
        <rationale>Empty quadrants reveal market gaps; overcrowded quadrants signal where differentiation is hardest. Visual mapping surfaces the whitespace that a feature list alone obscures.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <p>Axes: Premium vs Budget (vertical), Narrow vs Broad feature set (horizontal). Quadrants: Specialized/High Value, Enterprise/High Price, Niche/Underserved, Mass Market/Crowded.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="8-dimension-analysis">
      <p>Comprehensive multi-dimensional competitive assessment framework covering product, pricing, positioning, technology, traction, team, marketing, and weaknesses.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Analyse each competitor across all 8 dimensions. Do not skip dimensions—missing ones leave blind spots that surface in the gap analysis.</statement>
        <rationale>A partial analysis produces a partial gap table. Investors and customers will probe the dimensions you skipped.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <list>
        <item>Product—what features exist, what is missing</item>
        <item>Pricing—model, tiers, effective monthly cost for 1 user billed monthly</item>
        <item>Positioning—target audience, headline message</item>
        <item>Technology—stack, integrations, API availability</item>
        <item>Traction—estimated users, revenue proxy, growth signal</item>
        <item>Team—size, expertise, funding</item>
        <item>Marketing—channels, content cadence, ad spend signals</item>
        <item>Weaknesses—1-star reviews, forum complaints, missing features</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="gap-analysis">
      <p>Identifying and categorizing gaps across five types: feature, quality, audience, price, and experience.</p>

      <p>Five gap types to identify: feature gap (they do not have it), quality gap (they do it poorly), audience gap (they do not serve this segment), price gap (they are too expensive for some), experience gap (UX or onboarding is painful).</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Differentiate on a competitor weakness, not on feature parity. Scrape 1-star reviews and convert the top 3 complaints into your positioning message.</statement>
        <rationale>Copying competitors produces table-stakes features. Converting their biggest complaints into your headline creates a concrete, testable claim that resonates with dissatisfied users already searching for alternatives.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="differentiation-statement">
      <p>Formalizing the positioning statement to ensure differentiation is concrete and usable in marketing.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Write a positioning statement in the canonical template form before finalizing the gap analysis.</statement>
        <rationale>Forces the team to articulate the differentiation concretely and reveals whether the gap identified is actually usable as messaging.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Positioning Statement Template">
        <code lang="markdown"><![CDATA[
For solo freelancers
Who need simple project tracking
TaskLite is a project management tool
That focuses on single-person workflows
Unlike Asana or Monday
We have no team features, just personal productivity
        ]]></code>
        <note>Naming the competitor makes the claim testable and immediately clear to the target customer.</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="note-taking-app-example">
      <p>Worked example: market for personal knowledge management with competitor landscape and positioning.</p>

      <example type="good" title="Note-Taking App Analysis">
        <note>Market: personal knowledge management. Competitors analysed: Notion, Obsidian, Roam Research (direct); Apple Notes, Google Docs (indirect); AI writing tools (future).</note>
        <code lang="markdown"><![CDATA[
| Competitor | Strength         | Weakness              | Opportunity           |
|------------|------------------|-----------------------|-----------------------|
| Notion     | All-in-one       | Slow, complex         | Speed, simplicity     |
| Obsidian   | Local-first      | Steep learning curve  | Easier onboarding     |
| Roam       | Backlinks        | Expensive, dated UI   | Better UX, lower price|

Positioning: "For busy professionals who want fast, simple notes with linking.
Unlike Notion, we're single-purpose and lightning fast.
Unlike Obsidian, we work great out of the box."
        ]]></code>
        <note>Gap chosen: experience gap (speed and simplicity). Messaging names specific competitors to make the claim credible.</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="email-marketing-example">
      <p>Worked example: email marketing for solopreneurs where gap is discovered through pricing analysis.</p>

      <example type="good" title="Email Marketing for Solopreneurs">
        <note>Gap discovered through pricing analysis: all tools price by subscriber count, creating early paywalls for solopreneurs under 1000 subscribers.</note>
        <code lang="markdown"><![CDATA[
Opportunity: "Generous free tier (5000 subscribers), solo-focused features, no team complexity"
Gap type: Price gap + audience gap—no tool focuses on sub-1000 subscriber solo operators.
        ]]></code>
        <note>Price gap and audience gap combined. Competitor pricing analysis identified the tier ladder, not just features.</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="common-mistakes">
      <p>Anti-patterns and pitfalls to avoid during competitive analysis.</p>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Analysing only direct competitors and omitting indirect and future types.</description>
        <reason>Indirect competitors are what customers actually use today; future competitors are the real threat in 18 months. Missing both produces a false sense of whitespace.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Surface-level analysis limited to homepage copy without digging into pricing pages, reviews, and feature documentation.</description>
        <reason>Pricing footnotes (annual lock-in, seat minimums, transaction fees) and 1-star review themes contain more actionable signal than marketing copy.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>One-time analysis with no refresh schedule.</description>
        <reason>A competitor matrix is stale within 60-90 days. Pricing, feature flags, and team size change frequently. Schedule quarterly re-runs with the same template to produce a diff.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Copying competitors' features rather than differentiating on their weaknesses.</description>
        <reason>Feature parity produces table stakes, not a positioning story. Your differentiation is their weakness as expressed in customer complaints.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="data-fabrication">
      <p>Critical failure modes around hallucinated data: funding figures, pricing footnotes, and ratings bias.</p>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Accepting funding figures, employee counts, or revenue estimates without a verified source.</description>
        <reason>Without Crunchbase API access, agents invent plausible numbers. Mitigation: hard rule "if Crunchbase API unavailable, write 'unknown'—never estimate". Mark every unverified number with "(est.)".</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Accepting a pricing number without checking effective monthly cost for 1 user billed monthly.</description>
        <reason>Shown price excludes annual lock-in, seat minimums, and transaction fees. Always ask "what is the effective monthly price for 1 user, billed monthly?" before accepting any pricing cell.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Trusting G2 or Capterra star ratings as objective quality signals.</description>
        <reason>Paid placement skews stars upward; incentivised reviews under-report weaknesses. Cross-check with Reddit and Hacker News sentiment before quoting any rating.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="scope-and-geography">
      <p>Geography pinning and future-competitor scope control to prevent skewed results.</p>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Listing 5+ future competitors with no concrete signal (job posting, acquisition, beta product).</description>
        <reason>Agents over-list "Google could enter here" type future competitors. Cap at 2-3 and require one concrete signal per future competitor or it inflates the threat map.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Pin target geography in every prompt and reject any competitor whose primary market differs from your target region.</statement>
        <rationale>Without geography pinning, agents return competitors ranked by Google's global SERP, which skews toward US companies even when the user's market is EU or APAC.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="context-management">
      <p>Managing context windows across multiple competitors to avoid synthesis degradation.</p>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Dumping raw scrapes from 10+ competitor websites into a single synthesis prompt.</description>
        <reason>Context overflows degrade gap analysis quality. Pre-summarise each competitor to the snapshot template (one Task call per competitor), then synthesise the summaries in a final pass.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Run per-competitor snapshot tasks in parallel, synthesis serially. Cuts wall-clock by 5-8x and isolates per-competitor context windows.</statement>
        <rationale>Each competitor's pricing page, review scrape, and feature list is independent. Parallelising collection then serialising synthesis is the only pattern that scales beyond 5 competitors without context degradation.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="human-in-the-loop-checkpoints">
      <p>Critical approval gates to prevent data fabrication and ensure quality downstream.</p>

      <list>
        <item>Approve the seed competitor list before deep dives—agents over-index on Google's first page and miss "what my friend uses".</item>
        <item>Review per-competitor snapshots for hallucinated facts before the gap analysis runs.</item>
        <item>Sign off on the differentiation statement before it lands in marketing copy.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>Recommended multi-agent orchestration pattern for scalable competitor analysis.</p>

      <p>Drive this with the faion-research-agent in mode: competitors as the orchestrator. It owns the 5-step framework (identify → map → analyse → gap → differentiate). Fan out per-competitor snapshot work to parallel sub-tasks (one Task call per competitor) so each runs in its own context window—this is critical because dumping 10 raw competitor websites into one prompt blows context and degrades the gap analysis. Reconvene results into the matrix and gap analysis in a final synthesis pass. Output goes to .aidocs/product_docs/competitive-analysis.md.</p>

      <list>
        <item>faion-research-agent (mode: competitors)—top-level orchestrator; owns framework, writes competitive-analysis.md. Model: opus (strategic synthesis).</item>
        <item>faion-research-agent (mode: pricing)—invoked as a sub-step for the pricing-tier comparison; produces tier-by-tier matrix. Model: sonnet.</item>
        <item>faion-research-agent (mode: niche)—chained after differentiation step to validate the chosen white-space is a real niche, not an empty quadrant for a reason.</item>
        <item>faion-domain-checker-agent—invoked if naming/repositioning falls out of differentiation; verifies any new brand candidates are buyable.</item>
        <item>Per-competitor fan-out: spawn N parallel Task calls (haiku for snapshot fill, sonnet for weakness extraction from reviews) to parallelise WebFetch I/O.</item>
        <item>faion-sdd-executor-agent—downstream consumer; reads competitive-analysis.md when scoping spec.md for a feature differentiator.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="cli-tools">
      <p>Agent-friendly tools for scraping, diffing, team detection, and historical data access.</p>

      <list>
        <item>curl + pup / htmlq—Scrape pricing/feature pages deterministically</item>
        <item>lynx -dump—Strip pricing pages to plain text for LLM ingestion</item>
        <item>gh search repos—Find OSS competitors and read their READMEs</item>
        <item>wget --spider --recursive—Map a competitor's sitemap quickly</item>
        <item>playwright (CLI/script)—Render JS-heavy pricing pages (Stripe-pricing-table style)</item>
        <item>jq—Filter Product Hunt / G2 JSON exports</item>
        <item>whois, dig—Founding date proxy (domain registration), MX records (email stack)</item>
        <item>tldr-bot / LinkedIn search via API—Team size sanity check</item>
        <item>archive.org wayback CLI—See competitor's pricing history</item>
        <item>searxng (self-hosted)—Bulk SERP scraping without API quotas</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="services-and-apis">
      <p>Paid and free services for competitor intelligence collection and enrichment.</p>

      <list>
        <item>SimilarWeb—Traffic estimates per domain; useful for "Est. Users" column</item>
        <item>BuiltWith—Tech stack detection; fills the "Technology" dimension</item>
        <item>Wappalyzer—Free for small batches; same role as BuiltWith</item>
        <item>Crunchbase—Funding, founding date, employees—official source</item>
        <item>G2 / Capterra—Reviews + ratings; respect robots.txt and rate limits</item>
        <item>Product Hunt—Discovery, launch dates, upvotes as traction proxy</item>
        <item>Visualping / Distill.io—Track competitor pricing/feature page changes; pipe to agent on diff</item>
        <item>AppFollow / SensorTower—Mobile competitor downloads + reviews</item>
        <item>Reddit (via PRAW)—"Alternatives to X" threads; weaknesses in the wild</item>
        <item>Hacker News Algolia—Sentiment + comparison threads</item>
        <item>Wayback Machine—Historical pricing/messaging changes</item>
        <item>Linkup / Tavily / Exa—LLM-native search APIs with cleaner snippets</item>
        <item>FireCrawl—Crawl + markdown-ify a competitor site for LLM ingestion</item>
        <item>Perplexity API—Cited summary of "competitors of X"—fast seeding step</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="best-practices">
      <p>Operational practices for high-fidelity competitor analysis and ongoing maintenance.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Seed the competitor list with humans + customer interviews before agents—agents over-index on Google's first page and miss "what my friend uses".</statement>
        <rationale>Algorithmic discovery is fast but biased. Human seed lists capture the substitutes customers actually use.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Force the agent to cite a URL for every factual cell (price, founding year, employee count); reject any cell without a source.</statement>
        <rationale>Sourced claims are auditable. Unsourced cells are liabilities in investor meetings and marketing copy.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Run snapshot agents in parallel (one per competitor), synthesis serially. Cuts wall-clock by 5-8x and isolates per-competitor context.</statement>
        <rationale>Each competitor's pricing page, review scrape, and feature list is independent. Parallelising collection then serialising synthesis is the only pattern that scales beyond 5 competitors without context degradation.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Always include "future" competitors (AI startups, big-tech adjacencies)—they are the real threat in 18 months.</statement>
        <rationale>Current market leaders do not predict category shifts. Future competitors require a concrete signal (job posting, acquisition, beta product) but must not be omitted.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Keep the matrix to ≤8 dimensions; more columns degrade the gap analysis signal.</statement>
        <rationale>Excessive dimensions dilute focus and make visual patterns harder to spot.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Re-run quarterly with the same template; diff the markdown to see which competitors moved.</statement>
        <rationale>Quarterly re-runs surface pricing escalations, feature launches, and team growth. A diff between two snapshots is more actionable than a one-time matrix.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Store the seed competitor list in version control (.aidocs/product_docs/_competitors.yml) so re-runs are reproducible.</statement>
        <rationale>Reproducibility enables credible quarterly diffs and prevents drift in competitor selection.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Mark every estimated number with ~ or (est.) and never let the agent strip those hedges in the synthesis pass.</statement>
        <rationale>Unhedged estimates in a published matrix damage credibility. Investors and customers expect transparency about data quality.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/competitor-report.md" purpose="Full analysis report skeleton (market overview, per-competitor deep dive, gap analysis, differentiation)"/>
      <template path="templates/competitor-snapshot.md" purpose="Quick single-competitor snapshot template for fan-out sub-tasks"/>
      <template path="templates/scrape-competitor.sh" purpose="Bash scraper: fetches homepage, pricing page, G2, Wayback for one competitor"/>
    </templates>

